</td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Do you think anyone will build a nuclear rocket?</span><hr size=1> NERVA's atomic reactor slagged itself as it ran, venting the melted reactor core out the exhaust.  This is not actually a critical design flaw as you can consider the reactor an expendable part, but it's not a very optimal design and it's definitely a &quot;dirty&quot; design.<br>
<br>
And yeah, I'm pretty sure people would consider atomic bombs (no matter how small or theoretically clean) going off as unacceptable.  While Orion is a technically feasible design, I can't imagine it ever being used for heavy lift on Earth.<br>
<br>
I don't see anyone building any sort of serious nuclear rocket until there's a running test model of a design that doesn't produce radioactive fallout and can be scaled up and used for heavy-lift off Earth.  I believe we're still very much in the research stage for nuclear rockets despite the NERVA work. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nintendonick>NintendoNick</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 53<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/30/04 7:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=384.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Do you think anyone will build a nuclear rocket?</span><hr size=1> How about that Am-242 reactor design? Uses more surface area to increase thrust and exhaust I think. Thin wafer like metal Americium. How dirty is that? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gcnrevenger>GCNRevenger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/4/04 8:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=384.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re:</span><hr size=1> Mmmm the trouble with nuclear engines <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>for launch</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is the thrust-to-weight ratio... NERVA wasn't ever considerd for ground launch since it was heavy, it was intended only as an upper stage or orbital maneuvering engine... Speaking of Nerva, even though some material was released, it is possible to make one that doesn't release much. There has to be an acceptable level.<br>
