<br>
However, I'm trying to be a cynical realist about the possiblity of a business (be it Boeing or Armadillo) building a nuclear-powered launch vehicle.  Any design that has a radioactive exhaust is taboo, won't happen, never, nada.  In Western culture, there is no amount of radioactive exhaust that would be &quot;small enough&quot; for a business to risk the hassle involved.<br>
<br>
A government might build one, but it would have to be a government that didn't have to worry about public opinion.  China comes to mind as a distinct possibility, especially if they're serious about a moon base.  This could force everyone else to go nuclear to compete, actually. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=akaimbatman>AKAImBatman</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/4/04 11:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=384.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> Nuclear engines will get built. There just isn't any other way of expending enough energy to go anywhere. However, it may take awhile before it's acceptable to build them, and the early designs will probably be space-only. Once people get used to the idea of nuclear propulsion (and see that it's no big deal) they'll be less likely to complain about launch solutions.<br>
<br>
