<br>
They also have a government with considerably more latitude in the areas that hold back nuclear propulsion in the west, public opinion and nuclear treaties.<br>
<br>
It's actually a fairly interesting scenario: China builds a heavy lift NERVA-type nuclear rocket and starts lofting literally tons of material into orbit.  In short order they have a rudimentary space station in orbit (by lifting a Skylab-esque single unit into geostationary orbit) and begin serious talk about establishing a lunar base.<br>
<br>
In that situation any other nation with space interests will be forced to develop their own nuclear-powered heavy lift vehicles to compete, though the US for example would likely try to leapfrog the Chinese by going for gas core nuclear or some other more advanced concept.<br>
<br>
It would be Sputnik all over again. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gennaro@nuclearspace>Gennaro</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/6/04 2:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=384.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Rockets</span><hr size=1> Chinese not smart enough? Actually, genetical IQ of Orientals exceed that of westerners. They are definitely smart enough. Communism is a cultural question but that's all over now.<br>
