NERVA to my knowledge is unfeasable for ground launch. It had a thrust to weight ratio of about 2.4 only for the reactor and pumps. Considering adding wet mass and casing to that it would never get off the ground.<br>
<br>
What about this idea for a ground launcher?<br>
<br>
Am-242<br>
<br>
Particle Bed Style reactor optimized for thrust. The development concept of this had a T/W of 8.6-14.0 (shielded). Maybe this can be improved?<br>
It is said to have been easier to maintain when it comes to replacement and servicing. Design factors also resulted in minimized shielding requirements. <br>
<br>
Maybe ammonia for working fluid instead of hydrogen. Although NH3 has more molecular mass than H2 it has a lot higher density, translating into more propellant per unit volume and thus lower overall mass.<br>
